														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4855434">
									

<p>Its anomalous properties meaning that only you can know it, and nobody else can guess it, makes it uniquely applicable as a password to my thinking. As for the uses not making sense, I dunno; I deliberately avoided directly explaining each scenario, leaving it up to the reader to figure them out. Won't work for everybody. These days my reviewers tend to demand that I spell everything out verbatim&#8230; not so, six months ago.</p>
<p>While I feel there's enough justification in the password's use, it's obviously up to you to decide what violates your own headcanon. For my part, I want to tell as many different stories as possible; if a particular story requires some out-of-character moves on the part of the Foundation to make it function, I work on the justification until it works for me. I don't write anything that I think directly contradicts the way the setting works, because that defeats the purpose of using the setting, but everyone's SCPF is different and it's cool that this doesn't mesh with yours. I wanted to write something like this, so I bent the rules until it fit; I'd do it again.</p>
<p>Thanks for the comment, the thoughts and the positives, much appreciated!</p>

