			<div class="content" id="post-content-4864845">
									

<p>Thanks! After starting with a Euclid, which happened because the idea I came up with ended up being that, I intentionally wrote Safe, Keter, and Thaumiel next as I proceeded through all the recognized classes. I then went off the deep end with all the esoterics I could bundle together in my normal-length arms with relatively small hands, which is turning out to be nearly all of them. I think the classes work really well as creative prompts. If you were to come up with a Safe, what would it be? What would be so dangerous as to necessitate a Keter class? This isn't to say you should start with the class and then write the SCP — in most cases that's an abominable idea — but as an experiment, I've found it pretty inspirational. My highest-rated SCP exists because I forced myself to think: what's a Tiamat?</p>
<p>I had fun with the log format; <a href="/scp-5751">SCP-5751</a> is a spiritual sequel in that regard. The idea of telling these mini-stories, and making them little puzzles for the reader to unravel, excited me. I've taken it up a notch in the companion tale series to this skip, starting with <a href="/character-development">Character Development</a>. Turns out the answer to the question I asked myself at the start of writing this article — &quot;How many weird ideas can you think of based on an unforgettable password?&quot; — is &quot;a lot.&quot;</p>

